"",
"  gnuplot> set term tkcanvas {interactive}",
"  gnuplot> set output 'plot.file'",
"",
" After invoking \"wish\", execute the following sequence of tcl commands:",
"",
"  % source plot.file",
"  % canvas .c",
"  % pack .c",
"  % gnuplot .c",
"",
" The code generated by `gnuplot` creates a tcl procedure called \"gnuplot\"",
" that takes the name of a canvas as its argument.  When the procedure is,",
" called, it clears the canvas, finds the size of the canvas and draws the plot",
" in it, scaled to fit.",
"",
" For 2-dimensional plotting (\"plot\") an additional tcl procedures called",
" \"gnuplot_init\" is created. It can be used to set variables containing the",
" plotting area: \"xleft, xright, ybot, ytop\" in screen coordinates, \"x1min,",
" x1max, y1min, y1max, x2min, x2max, y2min, y2max\" in plot coordinates. These",
" may be used for programming in Tcl/Tk.",
" If the \"interactive\" option is specified, mouse clicking on a line segment",
" will print the coordinates of its midpoint to stdout.",
" More advanced user actions can happen instead if the user supplies a procedure",
" named \"user_gnuplot_coordinates\" which takes the following arguments:",
" \"x1s y1s x2s y2s x1e y1e x2e y2e\", the coordinates of the start and the end",
" point in the two possible axis ranges.",
"",
" The current version of `tkcanvas` supports neither `multiplot` nor `replot`."
END_HELP(tkcanvas)
